The point (which is frequently lost in the rush to make a funny) is that any expungement which is vague enough to do this with is most likely also a bad expungement. And by  I mean the result of the author hoping that the reader will do most of the work of being scary or interesting, instead of coming up with something scary or interesting to tell the reader. (Which was the case in the example you're responding to.) Alternately, it's bad because the author knows what's supposed to go there, but hasn't left enough clues in the text as to what that is, which is also a flaw and should be corrected.

There are also cases where people do this just to score a laugh at the author's expense, of course, but the other thing is more common.







